member.summary:
Discovers, caches, and instantiates pipeline plugins. Uses IDMEEditor.assemblyHandler for discovery — the same mechanism as [AddinAttribute] connectors already used throughout BeepDM.
Typical usage:
var registry = new PipelinePluginRegistry(editor); registry.Discover(); // scan loaded assemblies var source = registry.Create<IPipelineSource>(PipelineConstants.PluginIds.DbSource);

example.code:
services.AddBeepForBlazorServer(opts => 
{
    opts.DirectoryPath = Path.Combine(basePath, "Beep");
    opts.AppRepoName = "MyBlazorApp";
    opts.EnableSignalRProgress = true;
    opts.EnableCircuitHandlers = true;
});

services.AddBeepForBlazorWasm(opts => 
{
    opts.DirectoryPath = "Beep"; // Browser path
    opts.AppRepoName = "MyBlazorWasmApp";
    opts.UseBrowserStorage = true;
});

services.AddBeepForDesktop(opts => 
{
    opts.DirectoryPath = AppContext.BaseDirectory;
    opts.AppRepoName = "MyDesktopApp";
    opts.EnableProgressReporting = true;
});

var host = Host.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
    .ConfigureServices((context, services) => 
        services.AddBeepForDesktop(opts => opts.DirectoryPath = basePath))
    .Build();

var beepService = host.UseBeepForDesktop();
Application.Run(mainForm);

services.AddBeepForWeb(opts => 
{
    opts.DirectoryPath = Path.Combine(basePath, "Beep");
    opts.AppRepoName = "MyWebApi";
    opts.EnableConnectionPooling = true;
});

member.summary:
A cluster of  nodes that exposes a single
 surface to callers.  All routing, failover,
affinity and policy fan-out are handled internally.

Usage:

var cluster = new ProxyCluster(policy);
cluster.AddNode(new ProxyNode("primary",  primaryProxy,  weight: 2));
cluster.AddNode(new ProxyNode("replica1", replicaProxy1, weight: 1,
    role: ProxyDataSourceRole.Replica));

// Register and use like any IDataSource
IDataSource ds = cluster;
var rows = await ds.GetEntityAsync("Orders", filters);

Creates a proxy with an explicit  as the single source of truth.
Pass a custom  to use a distributed circuit-state backend;
omit to use the default in-process store.

Server-side dispatcher: receives a ,
routes it to the appropriate method on the local -managed
 (or ), and returns a
.



This class has no dependency on ASP.NET Core.
Wire it into any hosting framework:



// ASP.NET Core Minimal API — Program.cs on Worker Machine
var dispatcher = new ProxyRemoteRequestDispatcher(editor, "MyWorkerDS");

app.MapPost("/proxy/execute", async (HttpContext ctx) =>
{
    var req  = await ctx.Request.ReadFromJsonAsync<ProxyRemoteRequest>();
    var resp = await dispatcher.DispatchAsync(req, ctx.RequestAborted);
    await ctx.Response.WriteAsJsonAsync(resp);
});

app.MapGet("/proxy/ping", () => Results.Ok("pong"));




The  is the name under which the
backing datasource (or ) is registered
in ConfigEditor.  When null, the dispatcher looks up
the primary datasource from the request payload.

An  that routes every operation to a remote
worker machine via an .



Drop this into a  inside a 
to make the cluster topology span multiple machines:


var transport = new HttpProxyTransport("http://worker-b:5100");
var remote    = new RemoteProxyDataSource(transport, "worker-b", editor);
cluster.AddNode(new ProxyNode("worker-b", remote, weight: 2,
    role: ProxyDataSourceRole.Primary));




All complex arguments are serialized as JSON before being sent over the wire.
All complex return values are deserialized from the worker's JSON response.

Parses a JSON-encoded rule tree into a . Expected JSON format (n8n-style nodes):
{ "rule": "Field.IsInRange", "params": { "Min": "0", "Max": "100" }, "children": [ { "rule": "...", "params": {}, "children": [] } ] }
The flat token stream represents a DFS traversal of the node tree.
